type="user">jms-00BH</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00BH.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Sections need not be embeddings">Sections need not be embeddings</fr:title><fr:taxon>Counterexample</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Although it is the case that a section in a 1-category is always a monomorphism, it is not the case that every section in an (∞,1)-category is an embedding. This can be seen in <fr:link
href="hottbook.xml"
title="Homotopy Type Theory: univalent foundations of mathematics"
addr="hottbook"
type="local">homotopy type theory</fr:link>, by considering the splitting <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {1}\xrightarrow {\lambda \_.\mathsf {base}}S^1\xrightarrow {!}\mathbf {1}]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda \_.\mathsf {base}]]></fr:tex> were an embedding, it would mean that its fibers were propositions: but the fiber of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda \_.\mathsf {base}]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {base}]]></fr:tex> is the loop space of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S^1]]></fr:tex>, which is a proper set (the integers).</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
